<aura:component extends="auradocs:topicPanel">

    <aura:set attribute="title" value="aura:set"/>



    <p>Use the <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code> system tag to set the value of an inherited or nested attribute.</p>

    <h2>Inherited <code>body</code> Attribute</h2>

    <p>Every component inherits the <code>body</code> attribute from <code>&lt;aura:component&gt;</code> so <code>body</code> has some special behavior with <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code>. See <auradocs:topicLink topic="helloFacets">Component Body and Facets</auradocs:topicLink>.</p>

    <h2>Inherited Attributes</h2>

    <p>As well as the <code>body</code> attribute, you can use <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code> with other inherited attributes. Use <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code> in a sub-component to set the value of any attribute that is inherited from the parent component. For example, if you have a component <code>cmpA</code> that has an attribute called <code>address1</code>, and you have a component <code>cmpB</code> that extends component <code>cmpA</code>, use <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code> in component <code>cmpB</code> to set the value of the inherited <code>address1</code> attribute.</p>


    <p>Here is <code>sample/cmpA/cmpA.cmp</code>.</p>

<auradocs:codeblock><![CDATA[<aura:component abstract="true"
         extensible="true">
    <aura:attribute name="address1" type="String" />
</aura:component>
]]></auradocs:codeblock>

    <p>Here is the <code>sample/cmpB/cmpB.cmp</code> component that extends <code>cmpA</code>.</p>

<auradocs:codeblock><![CDATA[<aura:component extends="sample:cmpA">
    <aura:set attribute="address1" value="808 State St" />
</aura:component>
]]></auradocs:codeblock>

    <auradocs:warning>This usage of <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code> works for components and abstract components, but it doesnâ€™t work for interfaces. If you want to set the value of an attribute inherited from an interface, you must redefine the attribute in the sub-component using <code>&lt;aura:attribute&gt;</code> and set the value in its <code>default</code> attribute.</auradocs:warning>


    <h2>Attributes on Component References</h2>

    <p>When you include another component, such as <code>&lt;ui:button&gt;</code>, in a component, we call that a component reference to <code>&lt;ui:button&gt;</code>. You can use <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code> to set an attribute on the component reference. For example, if your component includes a reference to <code>&lt;ui:button&gt;</code>:</p>

<auradocs:codeblock><![CDATA[<ui:button label="">
    <aura:set attribute="label" value="hello"/>
</ui:button>
]]></auradocs:codeblock>


    <p>This is equivalent to:</p>

<auradocs:codeblock><![CDATA[<ui:button label="hello"/>
]]></auradocs:codeblock>

    <p>A more powerful example is setting markup within <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code> instead of using the <code>value</code> attribute. In the <a href="https://github.com/forcedotcom/aura-note/blob/master/src/main/webapp/WEB-INF/components/auranote/notes/notes.app" target="_new">Aura Note sample app</a>, the <code>&lt;aura:set&gt;</code> tag specifies the markup for the <code>left</code> attribute of the <code>ui:block</code> element.</p>

<auradocs:codeblock><![CDATA[<ui:block class="wrapper" aura:id="block">
    <aura:set attribute="left">
        <auranote:sidebar aura:id="sidebar" />
    </aura:set>
    <auranote:details aura:id="details" />
</ui:block>
]]></auradocs:codeblock>


</aura:component>
